{"abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"An adaptive backend which uses different backends under the hood depending on the target operating system."}],"sections":[],"identifier":{"url":"doc:\/\/SwiftCrossUI\/documentation\/SwiftCrossUI\/DefaultBackend","interfaceLanguage":"swift"},"primaryContentSections":[{"kind":"content","content":[{"type":"heading","anchor":"Overview","level":2,"text":"Overview"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"The beauty of SwiftCrossUI is that you can write your app once and have it look native everywhere. For this reason I recommend using DefaultBackend unless you’ve got particular constraints. It uses "},{"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftCrossUI\/documentation\/SwiftCrossUI\/AppKitBackend","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":" on macOS, "},{"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftCrossUI\/documentation\/SwiftCrossUI\/WinUIBackend","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":" on Window, "},{"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftCrossUI\/documentation\/SwiftCrossUI\/GtkBackend","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":" on Linux, and on "},{"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftCrossUI\/documentation\/SwiftCrossUI\/UIKitBackend","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":" on iOS\/tvOS."}]},{"type":"aside","style":"tip","name":"Tip","content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"If you’re using DefaultBackend, you can override the underlying backend during compilation by setting the "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"SCUI_DEFAULT_BACKEND"},{"type":"text","text":" environment variable to the name of the desired backend. This is useful when you e.g. want to test the Gtk version of your app while using a Mac. Note that this only works for built-in backends and still requires the chosen backend to be compatible with your machine."}],"type":"paragraph"}]},{"type":"aside","style":"warning","name":"Warning","content":[{"inlineContent":[{"text":"When using ","type":"text"},{"code":"SCUI_DEFAULT_BACKE